properties.name: Armati Street
properties.description: Named for Pio Vico Armati (see Mathew, 1979), late 19th and early 20th century. Owned and operated multiple chemist shops on Flinders Street (Mathew, 2008, p. 10).
properties.refs:
Mathew, J. Details Armati Family [Letter to D. Armati]. (1979, August 03). Townsville, QLD.

Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Hamilton Street
properties.description: Named for Frederick Hamilton, hotel owner and butcher who was elected to municipal council for one year (Mathew, 2008, p. 58).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Sir Leslie Thiess Street
properties.description: Named for Sir Leslie Thiess, "the chairman of the Breakwater Casino operating company" (Mathew, 2008, p. 112).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Sir Leslie Thiess Street
properties.description: Named for Sir Leslie Thiess, "the chairman of the Breakwater Casino operating company" (Mathew, 2008, p. 112).

properties.name: Fryer Street
properties.description: Named for Frederick Augustus Fryer, "a shareholder and a director of the Cleveland Bay Express Newspaper Company [... and] licensee of the Townsville Hotel" in the middle of the 19<sup>th</sup> century (Mathew, 2008, p. 51).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Carter Street
properties.description: Named for Thomas Roe Carter, a businessperson who entered partnerships with Frederick Augustus Fryer (see Fryer Street) who later, "traded on his own account as T.R. Carter and Company" (Mathew, 2008, p. 28).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Carter Street

properties.name: Fletcher Street
properties.description: Named for Joseph Fletcher, businessperson who owned a butcher shop, timber yard, and "a soap and candle works." He eventually served as Alderman and Mayor of Townsville (Mathew, 2008, p. 48).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Little Fletcher Street

properties.name: Jones Street
properties.description: Named for Alfred Raymond Jones, owner of various properties with John Henry Mayer (Mathew, 2008, p. 69).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Jones Street
properties.description: Named for Alfred Raymond Jones, owner of various properties with John Henry Mayer (Mathew, 2008, p. 69).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Morris Street
properties.description: Named for William Thomas Morris, "auctioneer and commission agent, who was an unsuccessful applicant in 1866 for the position of Council Inspector of Nuisances" (Mathew, 2008, p. 87).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Paxton Street
properties.description: Named for W.H. Paxton, "master of the schooner Mystery, which was employed for labour recruitment in the South Sea Islands" (Mathew, 2008, p. 99).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Upper Clifton Street
properties.description: Named for William Clifton, merchant involved with the Australasian Steam Navigation Company and Clifton and Aplin Brothers (with William and Henry Aplin). He was also "vice-president of both the Hospital and School of Arts Committees in 1874 and was active in collecting subscriptions for the establishment of a grammar school at Townsville" (Mathew, 2008, p. 33).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Dibbs Street
properties.description: Named for G.S.B. Dibbs, "a member of the Townsville Harbour Board from 1943 until 1960" (Mathew, 2008, p. 41).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Tomlins Street
properties.description: Named for L.E.D. Tomlins, a solicitor and Chairman of the Townsville Harbour Board (Mathew, 2008, p. 118).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Anthony Street
properties.description: Named for Albert Joseph Anthony, Chairman of the Townsville Harbour Board in the mid 20<sup>th</sup> century (Mathew, 2008, p. 9).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Perkins Street
properties.description: Named for Patrick Perkins. While he became a politician, he is most known as a brewer, having opened the Toowoomba Brewery and creating the well regarded Castlemaine XXXX ale (Mathew, 2008, p. 100).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Rooney Street
properties.description: Named for the Rooney Family, developers who were responsible for "the Magistrate’s Courthouse, the North Ward gaol and Bartlam’s building" (Mathew, 2008, p. 108).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Allen Street
properties.description: Named for Samuel Allen, a businessperson and owner of a produce store on Flinders and a hotel. He later became an Alderman as well. (Mathew, 2008, p. 7).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Lennon Street
properties.description: Named for William Allen, banker and business manager during the middle of the 19<sup>th</sup> which included roles in "the Bank of North Queensland and the Townsville Gas and Coke Company" (Mathew, 2008, p. 75).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Martin Street
properties.description: Named for William Martin, business person who ran the The Great Northern Railway Store and opened the first shop on Ross Island (Mathew, 2008, p. 84).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: St. John Street
properties.description: Named for St. John Robinson, a subdivider, the son of Henry Frederick Robinson; the latter was nicknamed the "German Gardener" and served as the namesake of "German Gardens," (Mathew, 2008, p. 110). Today, German Gardens is known as Belgian Gardens, the re-naming a consequence of de-Germanification during the First World War (Centre for the Government of Queensland, 2018).
properties.refs:
Centre for the Government of Queensland. (2018). Belgian Gardens. Retrieved from https://queenslandplaces.com.au/belgian-gardens.
Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Robinson Street
properties.description: Named for St. John Edmund Robinson. A developer, he built a zoon and wildlife sanctuary at Mount St. John and, "In 1933 he organised the first bull fight to be held in Australia and five years later staged the first private air pageant of the Commonwealth" (Mathew, 2008, p. 107).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.
